ong>Theses</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This collection contains theses documents from the former sister colleges of the University of East Africa. Currently, more than 2,158 theses titles have been microfilmed, jacketed and are on microfiche. However,more than 2,406 titles have been microfilmed and jacketed but are yet to be labeled, typed and microfiche. Many more theses titles have been abstracted and compiled in the Database of African Theses and Dissertations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Manuscripts</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The collection holds Corry, Kiswahili and Arabic manuscripts. Over &nbsp;1180 titles of manuscripts have been microfilmed and out of these, 291 titles for Corry papers have also been microfiche. The rest, that is Kiswahili and Arabic manuscripts are yet to be labeled, typed and microfiche.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Liberation movement Materials</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The collection also holds the materials on Liberation Movements in Africa.</p>\r\n', NULL, NULL, '', '/institutes/library/east-africana-collection', '2017-11-24 10:35:00', 1, 31, NULL),
(213, 'Reference and Documents Delivery', 'Reference and Documents Delivery', '<p>The Reference Collection provides help to students, faculty and staff. It is open at 08.00 from Monday through Friday and closes at 16.00 hours. On Saturdays, it operates from 08.00 to 13.00 hours and remain closed on Sundays and Public Holidays. Reference staff assists patrons in the location, use, and understanding of information resources, teaches effective search techniques, and trains in the use of library resources. Services are provided in person at the reference desk, and by telephone, email, and chat. Users may also make an appointment for a consultation with a librarian.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><br />\r\nThe Reference Collection provides help to students, faculty and staf. It is open at 08.00 from Monday through Friday and closes at 16.00 hours. On Saturdays, it operates from 08.00 to 13.00 hours and remain closed on Sundays and Public Holidays. Reference staff assists patrons in the location, use, and understanding of information resources, teaches effective search techniques, and trains in the use of library resources. Services are provided in person at the reference desk, and by telephone, email, and chat. Users may also make an appointment for a consultation with a librarian</p>\r\n', NULL, NULL, '', '/institutes/library/reference-and-documents-delivery', '2017-11-24 10:12:45', 1, 31, NULL),
(214, 'Welcome', 'Karibu', '<p>The College of Information and Communication Technologies (CoICT) is among the colleges of the University of Dar es Salaam (UDSM) in Tanzania. It was established on 27th January, 2011 to address the increasing demand of ICT experts in the country by strengthening the University&rsquo;s teaching, research and public service in the ICT-related disciplines through a more efficient utilization of the available human and physical resources. The College is located at Kijitonyama Campus along Alli Hassan Mwinyi road about five kilometers from the UDSM Main campus (Mwaimu Nyerere Campus).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College offers undergraduate and postgraduate degree programs that stress interactions between lecturers and students who are committed to academic excellence. The College offers curricula that integrate scientific, ICT and engineering principles, practical laboratory and computer work, engineering design experiences culminating into projects by applying Problem Based learning approach to solve existing community challenges.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College offers 1 certificate programme, 1 diploma programme, 6 undergraduate programmes, 1 postgraduate diploma programmes, 7 Master of Science programmes and PhD programmes in ICT related areas hosted in two Departments namely:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Department of Computer Science &amp; Engineering (CSE)<br />\r\nDepartment of Electronics and Telecommunication Engineering (ETE)<br />\r\nCurrently CoICT is home to 116 academic, technical and administrative staff members and more than 1,200 students. Our mission is to ensure that we provide our staff and students an excellent teaching and learning environment to prepare our next generation of scientists, innovators, engineers and experts that will move our country and the region forward.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College houses The Centre for Virtual Learning (CVL) which is a unit within CoICT responsible for providing technical support to all UDSM academic units in the design and provision of ICT-mediated distance learning programmes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College has an incubator unit known as University of Dar es Salaam Information and Communication Technology Incubator (UDICTI) which is a unit under the College with main objective of nurturing UDSM students who wish to establish their own ICT related businesses by develop their ideas into sustainable businesses done by offering incubation training.</p>\r\n', '<p>The College of Information and Communication Technologies (CoICT) is among the colleges of the University of Dar es Salaam (UDSM) in Tanzania. It was established on 27th January, 2011 to address the increasing demand of ICT experts in the country by strengthening the University&rsquo;s teaching, research and public service in the ICT-related disciplines through a more efficient utilization of the available human and physical resources. The College is located at Kijitonyama Campus along Alli Hassan Mwinyi road about five kilometers from the UDSM Main campus (Mwaimu Nyerere Campus).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College offers undergraduate and postgraduate degree programs that stress interactions between lecturers and students who are committed to academic excellence. The College offers curricula that integrate scientific, ICT and engineering principles, practical laboratory and computer work, engineering design experiences culminating into projects by applying Problem Based learning approach to solve existing community challenges.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College offers 1 certificate programme, 1 diploma programme, 6 undergraduate programmes, 1 postgraduate diploma programmes, 7 Master of Science programmes and PhD programmes in ICT related areas hosted in two Departments namely:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Department of Computer Science &amp; Engineering (CSE)<br />\r\nDepartment of Electronics and Telecommunication Engineering (ETE)<br />\r\nCurrently CoICT is home to 116 academic, technical and administrative staff members and more than 1,200 students. Our mission is to ensure that we provide our staff and students an excellent teaching and learning environment to prepare our next generation of scientists, innovators, engineers and experts that will move our country and the region forward.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College houses The Centre for Virtual Learning (CVL) which is a unit within CoICT responsible for providing technical support to all UDSM academic units in the design and provision of ICT-mediated distance learning programmes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The College has an incubator unit known as University of Dar es Salaam Information and Communication Technology Incubator (UDICTI) which is a unit under the College with main objective of nurturing UDSM students who wish to establish their own ICT related businesses by develop their ideas into sustainable businesses done by offering incubation training.</p>\r\n', NULL, NULL, '', '/colleges/coict/welcome', '2017-12-03 12:39:18', 1, 4, NULL),
(215, 'Departments and Units', 'Departments and Units', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong> Academic Departments</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012/13, the six major academic departments were Chemical and Mining Engineering (CME), Electrical Engineering (EE), Mechanical and Industrial Engineering (MIE), Structural and Construction Engineering (SCE), Transportation and Geotechnical Engineering (TGE) and Water Resources Engineering (WRE).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These departments provide undergraduate and postgraduate engineering education, research and outreach programs devoted to improve product quality, plant capacity utilization and product diversification.&nbsp; Besides, they provide expert professional services in the form of consultancy and services to industry, government and other organizations.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Chemical and Mining Engineering (CME)</strong> provides education, research and outreach focusing on the sustainable development of chemicals, materials, minerals and the science and technology of non-renewable resources products from natural and recycled materials.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Ambrose J. Itika.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Electrical Engineering (EE)</strong> serves the Tanzanian society by providing education, research, and public outreach programs in electrical engineering for the benefit of the nation, and the international community.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Acting Head of Department was Dr. Mighanda J. Manyahi.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Mechanical and Industrial Engineering (MIE)</strong> provides training, research and public services through consultancy in the fields of mechanical engineering, industrial engineering as well as in textile engineering and design. Mechanical engineering covers sub-disciplines of energy production and applications, manufacturing and design of mechanical and related systems. The industrial engineering and textile fields cover optimization of industrial, product and service delivery, and design, production and processing of materials for textile products, respectively.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Bwire Ndazi.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Structural and Construction Engineering (SCE)</strong> provides structural and construction engineers capable of designing and constructing engineering projects.&nbsp; In 2012/13 the Department was headed by Dr. John K. Makunza.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Transportation and Geotechnical Engineering (TGE) </strong>deals with the planning, design, operation, and management of transportation facilities.&nbsp; Besides, TGE provides geotechnical engineers capable of working with data from soil and rock samples to specify the requirements for man-made structures and earthworks that will be built on a site. These structures include shallow foundations (footings), deep foundations (piles and drilled piers), retaining walls, dams, embankments etc.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Hannibal Bwire.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Water Resources Engineering (WRE)</strong> offers programmes in the fields of water resources, environmental and sanitation engineering.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Joel Norbert;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp; Training Workshops Department (TW)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Training Workshops Department (TW) provides practical training skills in various engineering disciplines, which are organised into eight individual workshops including Carpentry; Masonry; Welding, Forging and Casting; Electrical; Bench Work; Machine Shop Practice; Electronics; and Chemical and Process Engineering.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of TW was Ms. Allida S. Kyoro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Coordinators of Academic Affairs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012/2013, coordinators of academic affairs included the Undergraduate Studies Coordinator; Postgraduate Studies and Research Coordinator; Time Table Coordinator; Practical Training Coordinator; and Chief Editor of the Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology (TJET) and Publications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Office of Postgraduate Studies and Research (PGS&amp;R)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Office of Postgraduate Studies and Research coordinates all activities related to postgraduate programmes and affairs, which include teaching and learning, research, projects and others. In the year 2012/13, Dr. Oscar Kibazohi was the Coordinator of Postgraduate Studies and Research.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(ii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Office of Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology (TJET) and Publications</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Office of publications was responsible with the coordination of all publications at the College specifically submissions to the Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology and other journals in the country and abroad. In year 2012/13, Prof. Aloyce W. Mayo coordinated all matters related to publications as well as the Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology (TJET).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(iii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Office of Undergraduate Studies (UGS)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Office of Undergraduate Studies coordinates all activities related to undergraduate academic programmes and affairs, which include teaching and learning, final year students&#39; projects and others. &nbsp;In year 2012/13, Dr. Pancras M. S. Bujulu was the Coordinator of Undergraduate Studies at College level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(iv)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Practical Training (PT) Office</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Office coordinates Practical Training (PT) activities of undergraduate students in industries and other related matters.&nbsp; In 2012/13, Dr. Tito E. Mwinuka coordinated all matters related to practical training to industry at College level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(v)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The College Time Table Coordinator</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Time Table Coordinator was responsible for coordinating all matters related to the College teaching and examinations time table and ensuring that class schedules run smoothly. Dr. Deogratius M. M. Mulungu coordinated all matters related to the College timetable in the year 2012/13.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp; College Planning and Resource Mobilization (P&amp;RM) Office</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof. Nurdin K. Mushule was the Coordinator of Planning and Resource Mobilization in the year 2012/2013.&nbsp; He was in charge of all matters related to planning and resource mobilization at College level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;College Finance Office (CFO)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>This Unit controlled and administered all College financial matters which include college funds and accounts.&nbsp; In 2012/2013, Dr. Karim Baruti was the College Financial Controller and Ms. Stella Aloyce was the College Accountant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Technical Services (CTS)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The CTS Department provides technical services to the College including maintenance, rehabilitation, repairs and transport services. CTS Department was also responsible for the oversight of store and procurement services.&nbsp; In 2012/2013, the CTS Department was headed by Mr. Richard Y. Kavana.</p>\r\n', '<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong> Academic Departments</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012/13, the six major academic departments were Chemical and Mining Engineering (CME), Electrical Engineering (EE), Mechanical and Industrial Engineering (MIE), Structural and Construction Engineering (SCE), Transportation and Geotechnical Engineering (TGE) and Water Resources Engineering (WRE).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These departments provide undergraduate and postgraduate engineering education, research and outreach programs devoted to improve product quality, plant capacity utilization and product diversification.&nbsp; Besides, they provide expert professional services in the form of consultancy and services to industry, government and other organizations.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Chemical and Mining Engineering (CME)</strong> provides education, research and outreach focusing on the sustainable development of chemicals, materials, minerals and the science and technology of non-renewable resources products from natural and recycled materials.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Ambrose J. Itika.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Electrical Engineering (EE)</strong> serves the Tanzanian society by providing education, research, and public outreach programs in electrical engineering for the benefit of the nation, and the international community.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Acting Head of Department was Dr. Mighanda J. Manyahi.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Mechanical and Industrial Engineering (MIE)</strong> provides training, research and public services through consultancy in the fields of mechanical engineering, industrial engineering as well as in textile engineering and design. Mechanical engineering covers sub-disciplines of energy production and applications, manufacturing and design of mechanical and related systems. The industrial engineering and textile fields cover optimization of industrial, product and service delivery, and design, production and processing of materials for textile products, respectively.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Bwire Ndazi.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Structural and Construction Engineering (SCE)</strong> provides structural and construction engineers capable of designing and constructing engineering projects.&nbsp; In 2012/13 the Department was headed by Dr. John K. Makunza.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Transportation and Geotechnical Engineering (TGE) </strong>deals with the planning, design, operation, and management of transportation facilities.&nbsp; Besides, TGE provides geotechnical engineers capable of working with data from soil and rock samples to specify the requirements for man-made structures and earthworks that will be built on a site. These structures include shallow foundations (footings), deep foundations (piles and drilled piers), retaining walls, dams, embankments etc.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Hannibal Bwire.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Department of Water Resources Engineering (WRE)</strong> offers programmes in the fields of water resources, environmental and sanitation engineering.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of Department was Dr. Joel Norbert;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp; Training Workshops Department (TW)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Training Workshops Department (TW) provides practical training skills in various engineering disciplines, which are organised into eight individual workshops including Carpentry; Masonry; Welding, Forging and Casting; Electrical; Bench Work; Machine Shop Practice; Electronics; and Chemical and Process Engineering.&nbsp; In 2012/13, the Head of TW was Ms. Allida S. Kyoro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Coordinators of Academic Affairs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012/2013, coordinators of academic affairs included the Undergraduate Studies Coordinator; Postgraduate Studies and Research Coordinator; Time Table Coordinator; Practical Training Coordinator; and Chief Editor of the Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology (TJET) and Publications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(i)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Office of Postgraduate Studies and Research (PGS&amp;R)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Office of Postgraduate Studies and Research coordinates all activities related to postgraduate programmes and affairs, which include teaching and learning, research, projects and others. In the year 2012/13, Dr. Oscar Kibazohi was the Coordinator of Postgraduate Studies and Research.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(ii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Office of Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology (TJET) and Publications</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Office of publications was responsible with the coordination of all publications at the College specifically submissions to the Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology and other journals in the country and abroad. In year 2012/13, Prof. Aloyce W. Mayo coordinated all matters related to publications as well as the Tanzania Journal of Engineering and Technology (TJET).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(iii)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Office of Undergraduate Studies (UGS)</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Office of Undergraduate Studies coordinates all activities related to undergraduate academic programmes and affairs, which include teaching and learning, final year students&#39; projects and others. &nbsp;In year 2012/13, Dr. Pancras M. S. Bujulu was the Coordinator of Undergraduate Studies at College level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(iv)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Practical Training (PT) Office</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Office coordinates Practical Training (PT) activities of undergraduate students in industries and other related matters.&nbsp; In 2012/13, Dr. Tito E. Mwinuka coordinated all matters related to practical training to industry at College level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>(v)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The College Time Table Coordinator</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Time Table Coordinator was responsible for coordinating all matters related to the College teaching and examinations time table and ensuring that class schedules run smoothly. Dr. Deogratius M. M. Mulungu coordinated all matters related to the College timetable in the year 2012/13.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp; College Planning and Resource Mobilization (P&amp;RM) Office</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof. Nurdin K. Mushule was the Coordinator of Planning and Resource Mobilization in the year 2012/2013.&nbsp; He was in charge of all matters related to planning and resource mobilization at College level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;College Finance Office (CFO)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>This Unit controlled and administered all College financial matters which include college funds and accounts.&nbsp; In 2012/2013, Dr. Karim Baruti was the College Financial Controller and Ms. Stella Aloyce was the College Accountant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Technical Services (CTS)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The CTS Department provides technical services to the College including maintenance, rehabilitation, repairs and transport services. CTS Department was also responsible for the oversight of store and procurement services.&nbsp; In 2012/2013, the CTS Department was headed by Mr. Richard Y. Kavana.</p>\r\n', NULL, NULL, '', '/colleges/coet/departments-and-units', '2017-11-24 10:28:43', 1, 5, NULL),
(216, 'Science and Engineering Collection', 'Science and Engineering Collection', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Science and Engineering Collection which came into existence in its current organizational format in July 2000, is a collection of materials on the following disciplines: Agriculture, Chemical Processing, Chemistry, Computer Science, Engineering (General), Forestry, Geology, Marine Sciences, Library Science, Mathematics, Medicine, Metallurgy, Nursing, Physics, Science (General) and Zoology. It consists of monographs, reports and serials in these disciplines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Physically, the Collection is divided into 2 sections: an open access section consisting of monographs and serials, and a closed access section which houses the Special Reserve Collection. The serials are open access but again must be read only in the closed section. Current issues of some 163 serial titles are displayed as a form of current awareness service. Each of the sections has a large reading area in addition to the shelved monographs and serials</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Collection offers the following services:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(i) Information to readers<br />\r\nThere is a formal Orientation Programme offered to First year students (Freshers), at the beginning of each academic year. This programme introduces the students to the Collection and registers them so that they can avail themselves of the services. Further information services are offered as requested by the users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(ii) Online Public Access Catalogs (OPACs)<br />\r\nAccess to the materials in the Collection is through OPACS, which were introduced in the academic year 2000/2001. Both monographs and serials including details of the holdings can be accessed through OPACs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n(iii) Loans of Materials<br />\r\nLoans are available for books on open access. The normal loan period is three weeks for students and faculty. The number of loans per user varies ranging from 5 books for undergraduates, 10 per post-graduate student and 20 per faculty member.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n(iv) Issue of Special Reserve Materials<br />\r\nMaterials from the Special Reserve Collection must be read within the Collection and are issued on short loan periods of two to four hours. There is a great demand for these materials since they are core reading materials that are available to a wide section of the students in the above mentioned disciplines. These materials are too expensive to be purchased individually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n(v) Production of Accession Bulletins<br />\r\nThe Collection produces an Accessions Bulletin regularly to inform faculty and students about new materials that have been added to the Collection. Some of the Accessions Bulletins have a supplement on the most recent serial titles on a selected topic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n(vi) CD-ROM and On-Line Databases<br />\r\nCD-ROM and Electronic databases are currently available in the Reference Department. CD-ROMs which cover the above mentioned disciples include: Compendex Plus, GEOBASE, LISA, Life Sciences Collection, POPLINE, TROPAG and RURAL, Environmental Abstracts, Applied Science and Technoogy Index, Derwent Biotechnology Abstracts, ISMEC and Science Citation Index.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Science and Engineering Collection which came into existence in its current organizational format in July 2000, is a collection of materials on the following disciplines: Agriculture, Chemical Processing, Chemistry, Computer Science, Engineering (General), Forestry, Geology, Marine Sciences, Library Science, Mathematics, Medicine, Metallurgy, Nursing, Physics, Science (General) and Zoology. It consists of monographs, reports and serials in these disciplines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Physically, the Collection is divided into 2 sections: an open access section consisting of monographs and serials, and a closed access section which house